{{Infobox baseball biography |name=Rick Camp | image = Rick Camp, former Atlanta Braves pitcher.jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Rick Camp greets other players before a Braves Legends Game in 2011. |position=[[Pitcher]] |bats=Right |throws=Right |birth_date={{Birth date|1953|6|10}} |birth_place=[[Trion, Georgia]] |death_date={{Death date and age|2013|4|25|1953|6|10}} |death_place=[[Rydal, Georgia]] |debutleague = MLB |debutdate=September 15 |debutyear=1976 |debutteam=Atlanta Braves |finalleague = MLB |finaldate=October 5 |finalyear=1985 |finalteam=Atlanta Braves |statleague = MLB |stat1label=[[Win–loss record (pitching)|Win–loss record]] |stat1value=56–49 |stat2label=[[Earned run average]] |stat2value=3.37 |stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s |stat3value=407 |stat4label=[[Save (baseball)|Saves]] |stat4value=57 |teams= *[[Atlanta Braves]] ({{mlby|1976}}–{{mlby|1985}}) }} '''Rick Lamar Camp''' (June 10, 1953 – April 25, 2013), was a professional baseball player who [[pitcher|pitched]] in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) from [[1976 Atlanta Braves season|1976]] to [[1985 Atlanta Braves season|1985]] for the [[Atlanta Braves]]. Long after his retirement, Camp served a federal prison sentence for convictions related to stealing money from a mental health center.<ref>"Rick Camp, 59, Pitcher gained fame for hitting his only home run in '85 game" (April 28, 2013) ''The Washington Post.'' Page C9 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/rick-camp-atlanta-braves-pitcher-dies-at-59/2013/04/27/20b9d020-aebb-11e2-8bf6-e70cb6ae066e_story.html]</ref>
==Biography== Camp was born in [[Trion, Georgia]], and was best known for hitting a game-tying 18th-inning home run on July 5, 1985, against the [[1985 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] with two outs and an 0-2 count off [[Tom Gorman (1980s pitcher)|Tom Gorman]]; this was the only home run of his nine-season career. Representing the tying run in the 19th inning, Camp struck out to end the game and was the losing pitcher. The Braves had run out of position players and had no choice but to let Camp bat in the 18th and 19th innings, even though his career batting average was .074. The game started on July 4 at 7:05 pm, but due to extra innings and three long rain delays, it did not end until 3:55 am on July 5, the latest any major league game has ever ended. (After the last out, the night still wasn't over: the Braves gave their fans a promised fireworks show at four in the morning.)
In September 2005, Camp was sentenced, along with four other people, including former Georgia State Representative [[Robin L. Williams]] to a term in federal prison for conspiring to steal more than $2 million from the Community Mental Health Center in [[Augusta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Sandy Hodson |author2=Tom Corwin |author3=Sylvia Cooper |last-author-amp=yes |title=Williams is guilty on all 17 charges, Jury also convicts four co-defendants of crimes |work=Augusta Chronicle |date=2005-05-05 |url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/050605/met_4082994.shtml |accessdate=2009-01-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905220946/http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/050605/met_4082994.shtml |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref> Camp received a three year sentence, while Williams got ten years. Camp remained friends with fellow conspirator Chad Long, grandson of Georgia Speaker of the House [[Tom Murphy (Georgia politician)|Tom Murphy]], even after their conviction for trying to embezzle money together. Camp died on April 25, 2013 at his home at the age of 59.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/breaking-news/former-braves-pitcher-rick-camp-dead-at-age-60/nXXhs/ |title=Former Braves pitcher Rick Camp dead at age 60 |publisher=www.ajc.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-07}}</ref>
